<div class="idea">
  <h2>Static Site Generators</h2>
  <p>There are <a href="https://www.staticgen.com/">lots of these out there</a> too, like <a href="https://gohugo.io/">Hugo</a> and <a href="https://jekyllrb.com/">Jekyll</a>. They pair nicely with static hosting. For example, <a href="https://www.netlify.com/">Netlify</a> can run your build commands for these static site as you commit to a Git Repo, or <a href="https://forestry.io/">Forestry</a> can add a UI (while still being Git-backed) on top of them. Other static site generators: <a href="https://www.11ty.io/">11ty</a>, <a href="http://www.metalsmith.io/">Metalsmith</a>, <a href="https://www.gatsbyjs.org/">Gatsby</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="idea">
  <h2>Data Storage</h2>
  <p>This is covered by all the major providers, but sometimes you need something simpler. <a href="https://webtask.io/">Webtask</a> gives you a small JSON store. <a href="https://airtable.com/">Airtable</a> and <a href="https://fieldbook.com/">Fieldbook</a> are a wonderful spreadsheet/data apps with good JavaScript APIs. Even <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/">Google Spreadsheets</a> has APIs, but can be improved with tools like <a href="https://github.com/jsoma/tabletop">Tabletop.js</a>.</p>
</div>